The article discusses the importance of investing in agricultural development to reduce hunger and poverty. It highlights that the majority of the world's poorest people rely on agriculture for food and income. The global economic and financial crisis, along with high food prices, has increased the risk of poverty for millions of people. The article emphasizes the need for a renewed commitment to agriculture development and reforming the international approach to food security. The US has announced its intention to double agricultural development assistance to over $1 billion in 2010 and seek to provide at least $3.5 billion over the next three years. Other countries are also making substantial commitments to agricultural development. The article outlines a new approach to food security, including strategic coordination of assistance, investment in country-owned plans, a comprehensive approach to investment, the role of multilateral mechanisms, and sustained and substantial commitment.